item.content:encoded:
[vc_row full_width="stretch_row" overlay_dotted="" css=".vc_custom_1546501281212{padding-top: 7% !important;background-color: #f9f9f9 !important;}"][vc_column][havnor_section_title title_text="General Questions" content_text="Find a short list of our most frequently asked questions." btm_space="5%"][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row full_width="stretch_row" overlay_dotted="" css=".vc_custom_1546501375443{padding-bottom: 10% !important;background-color: #f9f9f9 !important;}"][vc_column css=".vc_custom_1530614708280{padding-top: 0px !important;}" offset="vc_col-lg-6 vc_col-md-12"][vc_accordion one_active="true" title_size="22px"][vc_accordion_tab title="What is web hosting?" sub_title="Sub Title 1"][vc_column_text css=".vc_custom_1540362856773{margin-top: 0px !important;margin-bottom: 0px !important;padding-top: 0px !important;padding-bottom: 0px !important;}"]Web hosting allows you to publish your website. You will need a web hosting service to host your website so that people can view it online.[/vc_column_text][/vc_accordion_tab][vc_accordion_tab title="Do I need technical knowledge to use web hosting?" sub_title="Sub Title 2"][vc_column_text css=".vc_custom_1540362877479{margin-top: 0px !important;margin-bottom: 0px !important;padding-top: 0px !important;padding-bottom: 0px !important;}"]We’ve made our web hosting services accessible for everyone. We’ve designed our control panel so that it is easy to manage your domains and web hosting in one place. The FTP feature of our web hosting services makes it simple to upload your website. If you’ve never used web hosting before, our support team are available on the phone and online to help you get started.[/vc_column_text][/vc_accordion_tab][vc_accordion_tab title="How long does it take to set up web hosting?"][vc_column_text css=".vc_custom_1540362901835{margin-top: 0px !important;margin-bottom: 0px !important;padding-top: 0px !important;padding-bottom: 0px !important;}"]Setting up web hosting is quick and easy. It takes between 10 to 20 minutes for your web hosting package to be set up.[/vc_column_text][/vc_accordion_tab][vc_accordion_tab title="What do I get with web hosting from Speednames?"][vc_column_text css=".vc_custom_1540362922197{margin-top: 0px !important;margin-bottom: 0px !important;padding-top: 0px !important;padding-bottom: 0px !important;}"]You’ll get 3GB of web space, unlimited bandwidth, FTP access, databases, marketing tools, abiilty to manage unlimited domains in one place and friendly customer support for only €24.99 a year.[/vc_column_text][/vc_accordion_tab][vc_accordion_tab title="Do I need domain from Speednames to buy hosting?"][vc_column_text]Yes, each Speednames website hosting package must be associated with a domain name registered through Speednames to work.
If you have a domain name registered with another provider but would like to use web hosting from Speednames with it, simply transfer your domain to us before buying web hosting.[/vc_column_text][/vc_accordion_tab][/vc_accordion][/vc_column][vc_column css=".vc_custom_1530614727224{padding-top: 0px !important;}" offset="vc_col-lg-6 vc_col-md-12"][vc_accordion one_active="true" title_size="22px"][vc_accordion_tab title="How to search within a domain name?" sub_title="Sub Title 1"][vc_column_text css=".vc_custom_1546514753961{margin-top: 0px !important;margin-bottom: 0px !important;padding-top: 0px !important;padding-bottom: 0px !important;}"]If you're trying to find something on a site, and the site's own on-page search isn't working great — here's a little trick that works in Google, Bing, DuckDuckGo, and many other search engines: [/vc_column_text][/vc_accordion_tab][vc_accordion_tab title="How to lookup who owns a domain name?" sub_title="Sub Title 2"][vc_column_text css=".vc_custom_1540362985850{margin-top: 0px !important;margin-bottom: 0px !important;padding-top: 0px !important;padding-bottom: 0px !important;}"]Sometimes, but not always, you can find the owner of a domain by looking at the WHOIS information.
You can search for WHOIS information, and find out other details of a website, by using the tool on our homepage.[/vc_column_text][/vc_accordion_tab][vc_accordion_tab title="Who owns the domain system?"][vc_column_text css=".vc_custom_1540363003369{margin-top: 0px !important;margin-bottom: 0px !important;padding-top: 0px !important;padding-bottom: 0px !important;}"]The domain name system isn't owned by any one entity. It is, however, managed by the Internet Coorporation for Assigned Names and Numbers (ICAAN), a non-profit organization.[/vc_column_text][/vc_accordion_tab][vc_accordion_tab title="What is the best domain registrar?"][vc_column_text css=".vc_custom_1540363023497{margin-top: 0px !important;margin-bottom: 0px !important;padding-top: 0px !important;padding-bottom: 0px !important;}"]There are several good domain name registrars — and several you probably want to avoid. See our list of domain name registrars for our favorites.[/vc_column_text][/vc_accordion_tab][vc_accordion_tab title="How to find available domain names?"][vc_column_text]Any good registrar will let you search for domain names.
Namecheap has a really great search tool for finding domain names. They let you domain name options based on keywords, including new Top Level Domains.[/vc_column_text][/vc_accordion_tab][/vc_accordion][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row overlay_dotted="" css=".vc_custom_1546502006964{padding-top: 7% !important;padding-bottom: 11% !important;}"][vc_column][havnor_section_title title_text="Popular Questions" content_text="Then one day he was shooting at some food and up through the ground came a bubbling crude to the east side to a deluxe apartment in the sky." btm_space="5%"][vc_accordion accordion_style="style-two" one_active="true" active_tab="1" title_size="21"][vc_accordion_tab title="What to do when the domain names I want are not available?" sub_title="Sub Title 1"][vc_column_text css=".vc_custom_1540363065723{margin-top: 0px !important;margin-bottom: 0px !important;padding-top: 0px !important;padding-bottom: 0px !important;}"]You can pick a different domain name that is available, or you can try to buy the domain you want on the domain aftermarket.[/vc_column_text][/vc_accordion_tab][vc_accordion_tab title="What is domain backorder?" sub_title="Sub Title 2"][vc_column_text css=".vc_custom_1540363084744{margin-top: 0px !important;margin-bottom: 0px !important;padding-top: 0px !important;padding-bottom: 0px !important;}"]A domain backorder is a service provided by many domain name registrars that sometimes gives you the opportunity to buy domain names that have already been registered.
The registrar will watch the domain you want and attempt to register it immediately if it ever comes available.
This can be a good way to snag high-quality domain names, but it isn't a reliable way to acquire a domain name if you need one within a set period of time (for example, if you're about to launch a new web site).[/vc_column_text][/vc_accordion_tab][vc_accordion_tab title="How to backorder domain names?"][vc_column_text css=".vc_custom_1540363103168{margin-top: 0px !important;margin-bottom: 0px !important;padding-top: 0px !important;padding-bottom: 0px !important;}"]Each domain registrar handles back orders a little differently. GoDaddy is one of the largest providers of domain backorder services, so they are a good place to start.[/vc_column_text][/vc_accordion_tab][vc_accordion_tab title="How much to buy a domain?"][vc_column_text css=".vc_custom_1540363131824{margin-top: 0px !important;margin-bottom: 0px !important;padding-top: 0px !important;padding-bottom: 0px !important;}"]Prices for country code and new gTLD domains vary, but names with one of the "standard" domain extensions (.com, .org, etc.) should be under $10 per year. If they cost more than that, the reseller is charging too much[/vc_column_text][/vc_accordion_tab][vc_accordion_tab title="What is ttl?"][vc_column_text css=".vc_custom_1540363157066{margin-top: 0px !important;margin-bottom: 0px !important;padding-top: 0px !important;padding-bottom: 0px !important;}"]TTL stands for "Time to Live." It is one of the settings on your DNS setup, and it refers to the amount of time a router or server will store the the IP address information in your DNS record.
This has an effect if you change your DNS record. IF you have a very high TTL, some servers will wait the full time before re-checking where requests should be sent. This may lengthen the amount of time domain name propagation lasts.[/vc_column_text][/vc_accordion_tab][vc_accordion_tab title="How to edit TTL?"][vc_column_text css=".vc_custom_1540363176095{margin-top: 0px !important;margin-bottom: 0px !important;padding-top: 0px !important;padding-bottom: 0px !important;}"]TTL is one of the fields on a DNS record, so it is edited there. You can usually find it in your hosting control panel under something like Domain Tools or DNS Zone Editor.
Remember that TTL is one of the data points governed by TTL. If you change the TTL for a domain name from 864000 (24 hours) to 300 (five minutes), hoping that it will speed up global DNS propagation, servers and routers won't see the updated TTL until the check back for the entire DNS record. So, you might want to change the TTL a day or two before your change your IP address, if fast propagation is a high priority.[/vc_column_text][/vc_accordion_tab][/vc_accordion][/vc_column][/vc_row]

Together, we create enduring change and results." alert=".com $4.50 / .co $3.70 / .net $2.85 / .info $4.50" title_color="#ffffff" text_color="#ffffff" alter_text_color="#ffffff" button_bg_color="#167df8" button_bg_hover_color="rgba(0,178,68,0.01)" button_text_color="#ffffff" button_text_hover_color="#167df8" button_border_color="#167df8" button_border_hover_color="#167df8"][contact-form-7 id="312" title="Subscribe"][/hanor_forms][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row full_width="stretch_row" overlay_dotted="" css=".vc_custom_1546491537599{padding-top: 7% !important;background-color: #f9f9f9 !important;}"][vc_column][havnor_section_title title_text="General Questions" content_text="Find a short list of our most frequently asked questions." btm_space="55px"][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row full_width="stretch_row" overlay_dotted="" css=".vc_custom_1546511974029{padding-bottom: 10% !important;background-color: #f9f9f9 !important;}"][vc_column css=".vc_custom_1530614708280{padding-top: 0px !important;}" offset="vc_col-lg-6 vc_col-md-12"][vc_accordion one_active="true" title_size="20"][vc_accordion_tab title="Can I upgrade my WordPress Hosting plan?" sub_title="Sub Title 1"][vc_column_text css=".vc_custom_1540358539018{margin-top: 0px !important;margin-bottom: 0px !important;padding-top: 0px !important;padding-bottom: 0px !important;}"]We’ve made our web hosting services accessible for everyone. We’ve designed our control panel so that it is easy to manage your domains and web hosting in one place. The FTP feature of our web hosting services makes it simple to upload your website. If you’ve never used web hosting before, our support team are available on the phone and online to help you get started.[/vc_column_text][/vc_accordion_tab][vc_accordion_tab title="How to get a cheap domain name?" sub_title="Sub Title 2"][vc_column_text css=".vc_custom_1540358561885{margin-top: 0px !important;margin-bottom: 0px !important;padding-top: 0px !important;padding-bottom: 0px !important;}"]Many web hosting companies offer a free domain name when you purchase a hosting plan.
Unfortunately, these are usually only free for the first year. After that, you have to renew at a fee set by the hosting company — usually several dollars a year more expensive than if you were to pay for it separately directly from a domain name registrar.
Hosting companies also have a tendency to add-on additional charges like domain name privacy, which you can also get cheaper (or for free) from many good registrars.
If you'd rather purchase your domain name separate from your hosting plan (which is a very good idea), check out our list of domain name registrars for some of the better low-cost options.[/vc_column_text][/vc_accordion_tab][vc_accordion_tab title="How to get a .com domain?"][vc_column_text css=".vc_custom_1540358585115{margin-top: 0px !important;margin-bottom: 0px !important;padding-top: 0px !important;padding-bottom: 0px !important;}"]Just about every domain name registrar will be able to sell you a .com domain name.[/vc_column_text][/vc_accordion_tab][vc_accordion_tab title="Do I need a .com domain?"][vc_column_text css=".vc_custom_1540358607079{margin-top: 0px !important;margin-bottom: 0px !important;padding-top: 0px !important;padding-bottom: 0px !important;}"]No, there are many other options.
For example — if you are a non-profit organization, a club, a church, or another non-commercial entity, you may want to register as a .org domain name.
There has been a trend among tech-focused startups and open source projects in the last few years to use the .io extension.
For non-US entities, each country has its own country-code TLD, such a .uk and .ru. These are also popular for domain hacks — using the domain extension as part of the name of your site or brand.
There also, of course, the new "exotic" domain names, such as .ninja and .club. There are a number of these, and they might fit your brand very well.[/vc_column_text][/vc_accordion_tab][vc_accordion_tab title="Is .com domain still the best?"][vc_column_text]Even with all the additional options, .com seems to remain the gold standard for domain names. It carries a high-degree of trust with consumers, and communicates a sense of legitimacy that is hard to achieve with other domain name extensions. Because of this .com domains continue to have the highest sale price in the domain aftermarket.[/vc_column_text][/vc_accordion_tab][/vc_accordion][/vc_column][vc_column css=".vc_custom_1530614727224{padding-top: 0px !important;}" offset="vc_col-lg-6 vc_col-md-12"][vc_accordion one_active="true" title_size="20"][vc_accordion_tab title="How to buy domain names?" sub_title="Sub Title 1"][vc_column_text css=".vc_custom_1540358646895{margin-top: 0px !important;margin-bottom: 0px !important;padding-top: 0px !important;padding-bottom: 0px !important;}"]If you want to buy a domain name that no one else has registered before, that is very easy — just use any reputable domain name registrar.
If you are trying to purchase a domain name that has already been registered, you can do that as well. It can be a little more complicated than purchasing new registrations, though. Check out our in-depth guide to aftermarket domain purchasing for details.[/vc_column_text][/vc_accordion_tab][vc_accordion_tab title="How to sell domain names?" sub_title="Sub Title 2"][vc_column_text css=".vc_custom_1540358671399{margin-top: 0px !important;margin-bottom: 0px !important;padding-top: 0px !important;padding-bottom: 0px !important;}"]If you have registered domain names that you would like to sell, or are thinking about getting into the domain speculation business, there are a lot of details to consider. To get a good understanding of the issues, see the chapter on selling domain names in our Ultimate Domain Name Guide.[/vc_column_text][/vc_accordion_tab][vc_accordion_tab title="Do I need a domain name?"][vc_column_text css=".vc_custom_1540358694951{margin-top: 0px !important;margin-bottom: 0px !important;padding-top: 0px !important;padding-bottom: 0px !important;}"]If you want to set up a website, you probably need a domain name.
Some people set up free blogs or other types of sites using a domain name that belong to a third-party service like WordPress.com or Tumblr. That's okay for small personal blogs — but if you want to build a serious online presence, you really should have your own domain name.
It isn't hard to get your own domain name, all you need to do is buy one from a good domain name registrar.
If you're having trouble finding a domain name you like, or you want to learn more about what makes a good domain name before you purchase one, see our Ultimate Domain Name Guide.[/vc_column_text][/vc_accordion_tab][vc_accordion_tab title="Do I need multiple domain names?"][vc_column_text css=".vc_custom_1540358715983{margin-top: 0px !important;margin-bottom: 0px !important;padding-top: 0px !important;padding-bottom: 0px !important;}"]You usually want to focus your brand-building efforts on a single domain name. Especially if you're just starting to build an online presence for yourself or your organization, trying to build on multiple domain names can spread your efforts too thin.
However, it can be helpful to purchase additional domain names apart from your primary domain name. For example, if you have a .com, it's usually a good idea to go ahead and buy the .org version if it is available (and vice versa). It's also a good idea to buy common misspellings of your primary domain name, or other things people might accidentally type if they were looking for you.
[/vc_column_text][/vc_accordion_tab][vc_accordion_tab title="How to pick domain names?"][vc_column_text]Trying to figure out the best domain name for your new website is one of the more difficult tasks when establishing a new online presence. You don't want to change domain names often — it's bad for branding and bad for SEO — so whatever you diecide is going to have to work well for a good long time.
If you are an organization with a primarily offline presence, the best thing is usually to pick a domain name that is a easy-to-remember version of your real-world name. That might be your full business name, or a common, conversational shortening.[/vc_column_text][/vc_accordion_tab][/vc_accordion][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row full_width="stretch_row" overlay_dotted="" css=".vc_custom_1546519011199{background-color: rgba(22,125,248,0.91) !important;*background-color: rgb(22,125,248) !important;}"][vc_column css=".vc_custom_1546491589855{padding-top: 0px !important;}"][hanor_testimonial_carousel testimonial_style="testimonial_three" carousel_loop="true" carousel_items="1" carousel_nav="true" carousel_mousedrag="true" carousel_tablet="1" carousel_mobile="1" carousel_small_mobile="1" content_color="#ffffff" name_color="#ffffff" content_size="20" content_line_height="26" name_size="22" image_bg_color="#f9f9f9" star_color="#ffffff" active_star_color="#04d298" nav_arrow_color="#ffffff"][/vc_column][/vc_row]
